# Git and GitHub Commands

## Git Commands

### Configuration
- `git config --global user.name "Your Name"`  
  Sets the username that will be attached to your commits and tags.

- `git config --global user.email "your.email@example.com"`  
  Sets the email that will be attached to your commits and tags.

### Repository Setup
- `git init`  
  Initializes a new Git repository.

- `git clone <repository-url>`  
  Clones an existing repository from a URL.

### Basic Workflow
- `git status`  
  Shows the working directory status.

- `git add <file>`  
  Stages a file to be committed.

- `git add .`  
  Stages all changes in the working directory.

- `git commit -m "Commit message"`  
  Commits the staged changes with a message.

- `git commit -a -m "Commit message"`  
  Stages and commits all tracked files.

- `git push`  
  Pushes commits to the remote repository.

- `git pull`  
  Fetches and merges changes from the remote repository to the local repository.

### Branching and Merging
- `git branch`  
  Lists all branches in the repository.

- `git branch <branch-name>`  
  Creates a new branch.

- `git checkout <branch-name>`  
  Switches to the specified branch.

- `git checkout -b <branch-name>`  
  Creates a new branch and switches to it.

- `git merge <branch-name>`  
  Merges the specified branch into the current branch.

- `git branch -d <branch-name>`  
  Deletes the specified branch.

### Remote Repositories
- `git remote add origin <remote-url>`  
  Adds a remote repository.

- `git remote -v`  
  Shows remote repositories.

- `git push -u origin <branch-name>`  
  Pushes a branch to the remote repository and sets it to track the remote branch.

### Undoing Changes
- `git reset <file>`  
  Unstages a file.

- `git reset --hard <commit>`  
  Resets the index and working directory to the specified commit.

- `git revert <commit>`  
  Creates a new commit that undoes the changes from a previous commit.

## GitHub Commands

### Forking a Repository
- Go to the repository page on GitHub.
- Click the "Fork" button at the top-right of the page.

### Creating a Pull Request
- Push your branch to GitHub.
- Go to the repository on GitHub.
- Click the "Compare & pull request" button.

### Issues
- Click the "Issues" tab in the repository.
- Click the "New issue" button to create a new issue.

### Starring a Repository
- Go to the repository page on GitHub.
- Click the "Star" button at the top-right of the page.

### Watching a Repository
- Go to the repository page on GitHub.
- Click the "Watch" button at the top-right of the page.

### Viewing Repository Insights
- Go to the repository page on GitHub.
- Click the "Insights" tab to view analytics about the repository.


